<rss version="2.0" xmlns:atom="http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom"><channel><title><![CDATA[WSJ - EN-US - world]]></title><link/> https://www.wsj.com/news/world <atom:link href="https://rsshub.app/wsj/en-us/world" rel="self" type="application/rss+xml"></atom:link><description><![CDATA[WSJ - EN-US - world - Made with love by RSSHub(https://github.com/DIYgod/RSSHub)]]></description><generator> RS集线器</generator><webmaster>i@diygod.me (DIYgod)</webmaster><language> zh-cn</language><lastbuilddate> 2023 年 8 月 1 日，星期二 12:59:05 GMT</lastbuilddate><ttl> 120 </ttl><item><title><![CDATA[Beijing Area Hit by Deadliest Flooding in a Decade]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>台风“多克苏里”横扫中国东部地区 至少20人死亡19人失踪<!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001100639"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="467" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-827281?width=700&amp;height=467" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">台风“多克苏里”引发的洪水已淹没北京部分地区。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：托马斯·彼得/路透社</p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001100639"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline">作者： <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/rachel-liang" itemprop="url" rel="author">雷切尔·梁</a></span>和<span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/dan-strumpf" itemprop="url" rel="author">丹·斯特朗普夫</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 8 月 1 日上午 7:48 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/beijing-area-hit-by-deadliest-flooding-in-a-decade-73c571fc"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p>据官方媒体报道，台风“多克苏里”带来的暴雨造成洪水连续第四天，北京及周边地区至少有 20 人死亡，另有 19 人失踪。</p><p>截至周二，已有超过 5 万当地居民从家中撤离。据国有媒体《北京日报》报道，北京西部边缘的门头沟和房山郊区是受影响最严重的地区之一，一些地区报告出现电力和通讯中断。</p><p>据当地防洪抗旱办公室的一位官员称，截至早上 6 点，过去四天，这两个地区的降雨量已超过 16 英寸。这比他们预期的平均水平的一半以上，也超过了 2012 年该市上次<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10000872396390443437504577545020100937242?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">重大洪水灾害的</a>水平，当时有 79 人死亡。</p><p>该市门头沟附近的斋堂水库自1998年建成以来首次放水，而一份官方报纸则刊登了洪水淹没北京郊区一家豪华酒店大堂的照片。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-827284?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">周二，洪水席卷了北京郊区的妙峰山。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：Ng Hanguan/美联社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>在袭击菲律宾和台湾后，多克苏里周五上午在福建省登陆，然后继续向北席卷，给首都带来了十年来最严重的降雨。据北京电台报道，到周二下午，风暴已向东北方向移动，并可能减弱。随着市政府降低应急响应级别，市中心的一些公园于下午晚些时候恢复运营。</p><p>中国沿海地区经常受到太平洋热带风暴的袭击，但多克苏里带来的降雨和洪水规模却不同寻常。除了周边的河北省（据报道有 9 人死亡、6 人失踪）和附近的港口城市天津外，风暴还给东北部约 600 英里的吉林省和广东省带来了大雨。据国家气象中心称，向南数千英里。</p><p>与此同时，据该中心称，第二场台风正在中国大陆沿海盘旋。该中心表示，预计卡努将在未来几天登陆浙江或福建地区，威胁进一步洪水，但北京面临的风险较低。</p><p>据中国官方新华社报道，上个月，西南特大城市重庆发生严重洪涝，造成 15 人死亡，造成广泛破坏，迫使数千人撤离家园。</p><p>重庆发生洪灾之前，中国北方发生热浪，气温飙升至华氏100多度。据国营《环球时报》报道，中国国家气候中心上个月表示，中国出现了过去六十年来最高的高温天数，其中北京、邻近的天津和河北省遭受了最严重的高温。</p><p>写信给 Rachel Liang <a href="mailto:rachel.liang@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">（rachel.liang@wsj.com）</a>和 Dan Strumpf（ <a href="mailto:Dan.Strumpf@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">Dan.Strumpf@ws​​j.com）</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Tue, 01 Aug 2023 11:48:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/beijing-area-hit-by-deadliest-flooding-in-a-decade-73c571fc</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/beijing-area-hit-by-deadliest-flooding-in-a-decade-73c571fc<author><![CDATA[Rachel LiangDan Strumpf]]></author><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>灾害/事故</category><category>洪水/海啸</category><category>飓风/台风</category><category>风暴</category><category>自然灾害</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>天气</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>灾难</category><category>事故</category><category>洪水</category><category>潮汐波</category><category>飓风</category><category>台风</category><category>风暴</category><category>自然灾害</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>天气</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[China Replaces Missile Commander Days After Removing Foreign Minister]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>分析人士称，罢免高级军事领导人旨在增强对习近平的忠诚度<!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001100372"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-827252?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">中国领导人习近平晋升中国人民解放军火箭军新任司令员王厚斌和新任政治委员徐锡胜为上将军衔。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：李刚/祖玛出版社</p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001100372"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline">作者： <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/alastair-gale" itemprop="url" rel="author">阿拉斯泰尔·盖尔 (Alastair Gale)</a></span>和<span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/chunhan-wong" itemprop="url" rel="author">黄春汉 (Chun Han Wong)</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 8 月 1 日上午 6:40 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/china-replaces-missile-commander-days-after-removing-foreign-minister-86b0af9b"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p>中国罢黜了导弹部队司令，分析人士称此举是为了确保军队对领导人习近平的忠诚，这支军队控制着针对美国的核弹头导弹，并将在任何夺取美国领土的企图中发挥关键作用。台湾通过武力。</p><p>中国人民解放军火箭军老兵李玉超的免职，标志着他在重要军事岗位上异常短暂的任期的突然结束，而几天前<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/china-foreign-minister-qin-gang-replaced-63660fad?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">，中国又做出了一项神秘的决定，更换了外交部长</a>。</p><p>去年1月被任命为司令员的李已经好几个月没有在公开场合露面了。周二，中国庆祝中国人民解放军成立 96 周年，前一天举行的仪式上确认了他的下台。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=9F7AF9B6-88BC-4AB6-B4C8-E0CF0C68E116&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fchina-replaces-missile-commander-days-after-removing-foreign-minister-86b0af9b&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption">北京在周二的紧急会议上重新任命最高外交官王毅接替秦刚担任外交部长，但没有提及秦刚神秘缺席的问题。中国领导人习近平七个月前亲自挑选了秦国。照片：Florence Lo/Pool 路透社/美联社<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div><p>在周二的周年纪念评论中，官方报纸《解放军报》敦促全体军人维护习近平作为共产党领导“核心”的地位，并坚持不懈地在军队内部执行纪律和反腐败工作。</p><p>据官方消息，在一天前的仪式上，习近平正式晋升中国人民解放军火箭军新任司令员王厚斌和新任政治委员徐锡胜为上将军衔，并向他们授予新军衔徽章。新华社．王和徐分别拥有海军和空军背景，他们的任命背离了中国战略导弹部队由具有该军种经验的军官指挥的长期做法。</p><p>在中国对军队实行苏联式政治控制的情况下，解放军维持着双重领导体制，军事单位通常由两名同等级别的军官领导：一名指挥官，对作战决策拥有正式权力；以及执行党的指示的政委。</p><p>新华社的报道没有提及自 2020 年 7 月起担任这一职务的前任司令员李彦宏或政委。中国国防部没有立即回应有关李彦宏接替火箭军司令员的询问。</p><p>李克强离职几天前， <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/china-foreign-minister-qin-gang-replaced-63660fad?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">中国突然解除了外交部长秦刚的</a>职务，而就在秦刚上任几个月后，这是北京方面在没有任何解释的情况下做出的又一改变。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-827253?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">中国最近解除了秦刚的外交部长职务。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：Thomas Trutschel/DPA/Zuma Press</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>在秦被免职后不久，“对负责监督中国核武器计划的习近平亲信的前火箭军司令员李玉超的清洗标志着中国多年来最深刻的领导层改组之一，”高级研究员克雷格辛格尔顿说。保卫民主基金会，一个总部位于华盛顿的保守派智囊团。</p><p>习近平于 2012 年底掌权后，在中国军队中开展了大范围的反腐败打击行动，清洗了多名高级指挥员，其中包括 2019 年被判处无期徒刑<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/former-chinese-military-chief-sentenced-to-life-in-prison-for-corruption-11550666372" target="_blank" class="icon none">的前联合参谋长房峰辉。</a>尽管近年来披露针对高级军官的调查的情况有所减少，但称这些清洗对于习近平将解放军打造成一支现代化战斗力量的努力至关重要。</p><p>辛格尔顿表示<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/after-wagner-revolt-questions-of-blame-in-vladimir-putins-inner-circle-64c541ff?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">，俄罗斯最近发生的短暂武装起义</a>可能提醒人们需要严格控制军队。</p><p> “瓦格纳叛乱的失败几乎肯定强化了习近平对意识形态控制的执着，甚至不惜牺牲经济增长和中国正在进行的军事现代化，”他说。</p><p>解放军火箭军控制着中国的常规和核陆基导弹计划，包括能够到达美国本土的核弹头洲际弹道导弹。五角大楼在去年的一份报告中表示，北京近年来<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/china-is-accelerating-its-nuclear-buildup-over-rising-fears-of-u-s-conflict-11649509201?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">加快了核武器的发展</a>，预计到 2035 年，拥有的核弹头将从目前的约 400 枚增至约 1,500 枚。</p><p>美国战略司令部司令在今年早些时候<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/china-has-more-icbm-launchers-than-u-s-american-military-reports-11675779463" target="_blank" class="icon none">给国会的一封信中写道</a>，中国在西部沙漠地区建造了巨大的洲际弹道导弹发射井，目前拥有的导弹发射装置比美国还多。</p><p>尽管习近平领导了中国军队总体规模的缩减，但解放军火箭军近年来有所壮大，这反映出其对北京利用远程核弹头弹道导弹威慑美国和发展常规导弹的战略的重要性用于任何地区冲突的武库。</p><p>根据<a href="https://nonproliferation.org/wp-content/uploads/2023/07/web_peoples_liberation_army_rocket_force_order_of_battle_07102023.pdf" target="_blank" class="icon none">最近的一项研究</a>，过去十年，中国的战斗导弹旅数量增加了一倍。</p><p>解放军火箭军拥有数百枚弹道导弹，可用于瞄准台湾，企图强行控制该岛或<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/chinas-missile-threat-drives-new-u-s-approach-in-asia-95fc9a7b" target="_blank" class="icon none">威胁美国在日本和关岛的主要军事基地</a>。中国还<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/chinas-missile-threat-drives-new-u-s-approach-in-asia-95fc9a7b" target="_blank" class="icon none">部署了高超音速导弹</a>，美国一直在努力开发这种导弹，而且导弹防御系统更难摧毁这种导弹。</p><p>中国人民解放军火箭军正在增强可信可靠的核威慑和反击能力，加强中远程精确打击力量，增强战略制衡能力，建设强大的现代化火箭军。 2019年最新的国防白皮书。</p><p>新的领导层任命标志着从军队其他部门引进指挥官的罕见决定。王新任火箭军司令员，曾任中国人民解放军海军副司令员。新任火箭军政委徐是一名空军军官，最近担任解放军南部战区副政委，该司令部负责南海地区，而南海是中美<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/chinese-jet-fighters-step-up-pressure-on-u-s-aircraft-over-south-china-sea-c2d1ac88" target="_blank" class="icon none">军事冲突频繁的</a>地区。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-827254?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">北京阅兵式上展示的弹道导弹。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：Mark Schiefelbein/美联社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>关于李克强的副手刘广斌的命运也引发了猜测，他也已经几个月没有在公开场合露面了。官方媒体没有提及刘的地位，也没有提及任何替代者。</p><p>新的任命还意味着，火箭军现在有一位政治委员，其党龄高于指挥官，这是相当不寻常的。即将离任的司令员李和前政委徐忠波都是党的精英中央委员会的正式成员。</p><p>新任司令员王既不是中央委员，也不是无投票权的候补中央委员。新政委徐锡生是10月加入中央委员会的205名正式委员之一。</p><p>即使按照中国军方不透明的标准，与火箭军相关的细节也常常被严格隐瞒。</p><p>周一升职几天前，中国一家知名新闻媒体《澎湃新闻》援引已故军官的亲友的话称，一名前火箭军副司令于7月初去世，享年66岁。这份报告后来消失了。该报没有回应置评请求。</p><p>写信给 Alastair Gale <a href="mailto:alastair.gale@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">（alastair.gale@wsj.com）</a>和 Chun Han Wong（ <a href="mailto:chunhan.wong@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">chunhan.wong@wsj.com</a> ）</p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Tue, 01 Aug 2023 10:40:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/china-replaces-missile-commander-days-after-removing-foreign-minister-86b0af9b</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/china-replaces-missile-commander-days-after-removing-foreign-minister-86b0af9b<author><![CDATA[Alastair GaleChun Han Wong]]></author><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>国家/公共安全</category><category>武装部队</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>国家的</category><category>公安</category><category>武装部队</category><category>政治</category><category>国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[France Prepares to Evacuate European Citizens From Niger]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>亲俄罗斯、支持政变的抗议者周末袭击法国大使馆后进行疏散<!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001100512"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-827262?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">支持者在尼亚美国民议会前集会支持尼日尔军政府，挥舞旗帜。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：法新社/盖蒂图片社</p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001100512"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline">作者： <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/noemie-bisserbe" itemprop="url" rel="author">诺埃米·比瑟布</a></span>和<span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/gabriele-steinhauser" itemprop="url" rel="author">加布里埃尔·斯坦豪瑟</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 8 月 1 日上午 6:24 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/france-prepares-to-evacuate-european-citizens-from-coup-hit-niger-d46774af"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p>法国表示，在支持尼日尔上周政变的亲俄罗斯抗议者<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/west-african-leaders-threaten-force-against-niger-plotters-e046fae7?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">周末袭击</a>法国大使馆后，法国准备周二从尼日尔撤离本国公民和其他欧洲国家的公民。</p><p>计划中的撤离表明，法国和其他欧洲国家政府预计其公民在尼日尔面临更高的风险。尼日尔一直<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/niger-coup-upends-u-s-security-plans-in-west-africa-handing-russia-an-opportunity-8dcf6679?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">是美国和欧洲打击撒哈拉以南半干旱地带萨赫勒地区伊斯兰武装分子的重要盟友</a>。</p><p>西方官员担心，上周拘留尼日尔民选总统穆罕默德·巴祖姆的军政府可能会<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/in-need-of-allies-putin-courts-african-leaders-in-st-petersburg-b6596a7b?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">与俄罗斯发展更密切的关系</a>，特别是如果尼日尔前殖民国家法国和美国削减对军政府的军事援助。周日，数千名支持政变的抗议者向法国驻首都尼亚美大使馆投掷石块，其中一些人挥舞着俄罗斯国旗和标语牌，要求法国退出尼日尔。</p><p> “鉴于尼亚美的局势、前天针对我国大使馆发生的暴力事件以及领空的关闭，导致我们的同胞无法通过自己的方式离开该国，法国正在准备撤离其国民，希望离开该国的欧洲国民，”法国外交部周二在一份声明中表示。 “疏散行动将于今天开始，”它补充道。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-827265?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">抗议者举着从法国驻尼亚美大使馆拿走的标语。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：-/法新社/盖蒂图片社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>美国国务院、美国-非洲司令部和美国驻尼亚美大使馆没有立即回应有关华盛顿是否计划从尼日尔撤离美国公民的问题。</p><p>周一晚上，尼日尔的两个邻国马里和布基纳法索的军事领导人在<em>政变</em>后与莫斯科结盟，表示如果其他西非国家试图使用武力<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/niger-coup-leaders-detain-ministers-party-officials-6ba1efa1?mod=hp_lista_pos1&amp;mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">解放尼日尔军政府，</a>他们将帮助保卫尼日尔军政府。巴祖姆并让他重新掌权。</p><p>周日，法国大使馆遇袭几小时后，西非国家经济共同体领导人表示，如果政变策划者一周内不让步，他们将考虑对尼日尔进行军事干预。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=9B8EB2F8-7751-46ED-8D36-E964233A2505&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Ffrance-prepares-to-evacuate-european-citizens-from-coup-hit-niger-d46774af&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption">国务卿安东尼·布林肯周六表示，尼日尔的军事政变危及了美国价值数亿美元的援助和安全支持。欧盟还暂停了与尼日尔的安全合作和财政支持。照片：达伦·英格兰/Shutterstock<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div><p>法国外交部长凯瑟琳·科隆纳周一否认了尼日尔军政府关于巴黎将参与军事干预的说法。 “法国唯一的优先事项是其国民的安全，”她在晚间电视采访中说。</p><p>科隆纳指责军政府和俄罗斯对法国大使馆的袭击负责。</p><p> “我们（周日）看到的是一场有组织的、非自发的、暴力的、极其危险的抗议活动，其中有燃烧瓶、俄罗斯国旗、反法口号，都是从我们在其他地方看到的复制粘贴的，”她说。 “所以所有常见的俄罗斯-非洲风格的不稳定因素都是如此。”</p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"></div><p>外交部长表示，约有1000名法国公民居住在尼日尔，但其中约一半目前在国外度假。法国国防部表示，这一数字不包括驻扎在尼日尔并将留在那里的约 1,500 名法国士兵。</p><p> 2013年，在社会党总统弗朗索瓦·奥朗德的领导下，法国向萨赫勒地区部署了军队，帮助打击伊斯兰国和与基地组织有联系的武装分子。在马里和布基纳法索发生政变后，它被迫缩减在尼日尔的存在，并将精力集中在巴祖姆的盟友尼日尔。</p><p>美国还在尼日尔驻扎了约 1,100 名士兵，帮助训练当地特种部队并支持他们执行任务。该国还拥有美国无人机，并且一直是美国在萨赫勒地区反恐努力的核心。</p><p class="articleTagLine"> —迈克尔·M·菲利普斯 (Michael M. Phillips) 对本文做出了贡献。</p><p>写信给 Noemie Bisserbe（ <a href="mailto:noemie.bisserbe@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">noemie.bisserbe@wsj.com）</a>和 Gabriele Steinhauser（ <a href="mailto:Gabriele.Steinhauser@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">Gabriele.Steinhauser@wsj.com</a> ）</p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Tue, 01 Aug 2023 10:24:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/france-prepares-to-evacuate-european-citizens-from-coup-hit-niger-d46774af</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/france-prepares-to-evacuate-european-citizens-from-coup-hit-niger-d46774af<author><![CDATA[Noemie BisserbeGabriele Steinhauser]]></author><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>内乱</category><category>国家/公共安全</category><category>社会/社区</category><category>叛乱</category><category>犯罪/法律诉讼</category><category>国际关系</category><category>人类迁徙</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>社会问题</category><category>恐怖主义</category><category>军事行动</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>内乱</category><category>国家的</category><category>公安</category><category>社会</category><category>社区</category><category>叛乱</category><category>犯罪</category><category>合法举动</category><category>国际关系</category><category>人类迁徙</category><category>政治</category><category>国内政治</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>社会问题</category><category>恐怖主义</category><category>军事行动</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Myanmar’s Aung San Suu Kyi Gets Surprise Partial Pardon]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>赦免范围包括五项定罪，其中一项涉及对讲机。但这位前文职领导人仍将因其他罪行而服刑数十年。 <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001100460"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="613" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-827248?width=860&amp;height=613" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">赦免后，昂山素季将被监禁 27 年。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：nyein chan naing/Shutterstock </p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001100460"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/feliz-solomon" itemprop="url" rel="author">费利斯</a></span>·所罗门</div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 8 月 1 日上午 6:14 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/myanmars-aung-san-suu-kyi-serving-33-year-sentence-gets-surprise-partial-pardon-74eae973"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p>缅甸前文职领导人昂山素季在 2021 年的军事政变中被赶下台，并在军政府针对她提起的一系列案件中被定罪，其中一些罪行被赦免，将她长达数十年的刑期减少了六年。</p><p> 78 岁的昂山素季在 2021 年 2 月 1 日清晨的一次突袭中被拘留，当时军方推翻了她当选的政府，使这个东南亚国家陷入混乱。她随后被判犯有腐败和选举舞弊等 18 项罪名，总共被判处<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/aung-san-suu-kyi-to-serve-33-years-in-prison-after-series-of-trials-11672405999?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">33 年监禁。</a></p><p>军政府在周二在国家控制媒体上发布的一份声明中表示，昂山素季因其中五项罪行获得赦免，其中包括违反与 Covid-19 大流行相关的规定以及<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/after-myanmar-coup-aung-san-suu-kyi-accused-of-illegally-importing-walkie-talkies-11612361563?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">非法进口对讲机</a>。军政府发言人佐敏吞告诉记者，赦免将使昂山素季的刑期减少六年。这将使她在监狱中服刑 27 年，除非军政府做出涉及她的进一步改变或决定。</p><p>一位知情人士称，自 2022 年 12 月以来，她的法律团队一直未能与她会面，也未能证实有关昂山素季最近从<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/aung-sansuukyis-life-in-myanmar-prison-no-visitors-calls-or-news-11667080016?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">首都内比都的监狱</a>转移到一所房子的报道。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="463" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-827249?width=700&amp;height=463" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> 2015 年昂山素季在缅甸竞选。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：str/法新社/盖蒂图片社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>昂山素季领导的政党全国民主联盟在 2015 年历史性选举中大获全胜，这是该国 25 年来首次自由竞争的选举，并于 2020 年以压倒性<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/aung-san-suu-kyi-the-generals-and-how-myanmars-democracy-hopes-collapsed-11612542400?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">优势</a><a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/aung-san-suu-kyi-under-fire-abroad-wins-big-in-myanmar-election-11605248807?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">再次当选。</a>选举后召开第一次会议，拘留了昂山素季和其他官员，其中包括前总统温敏，后者周二也获得了部分赦免。</p><p>军方声称此次投票存在舞弊行为，但选举观察员予以驳斥。</p><p>政治分析人士表示，军政府可能打算通过周二的部分赦免来安抚外国政府，并做出一个小姿态，表明他们愿意改变。然而，分析人士表示，西方政府不太可能将这一发展视为真正的让步。</p><p> “我认为我们需要抵制住过度解读的诱惑。如果你看一下所有这些指控，你会发现他们显然是把她关起来并扔掉了钥匙，”泰国独立分析师、缅甸问题专家戴维·马蒂森 (David Mathieson) 说。 “缩短六年徒刑只是表明这些审判从一开始就是政治作秀，没有法治。”</p><p>政变突然结束了缅甸长达十年的民主转型，使该国重新回到<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/myanmar-coup-poses-diplomatic-challenge-for-world-leaders-11613049643?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">全球贱民的地位</a>，并随着西方政府实施制裁和投资者逃离而<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/myanmars-economy-is-in-a-free-fall-with-empty-factories-closed-banks-failing-internet-11618059258?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">使其经济陷入混乱</a>。主要由支持民主的年轻人领导的<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/a-new-generation-takes-the-lead-in-myanmar-protests-11615395087?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">大规模街头抗议</a>遭到致命武力的镇压<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/a-new-generation-takes-the-lead-in-myanmar-protests-11615395087?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">&nbsp;</a>并很快陷入武装叛乱。</p><p>军政府和武装叛乱分子之间的冲突此后蔓延到全国各地。军方试图通过不断升级的武力消灭对手，经常<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/myanmar-militarys-attack-leaves-village-in-ruins-strewn-with-charred-human-remains-7228843b?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">利用空袭轰炸涉嫌藏匿叛乱分子的村庄</a>。周一，军政府延长了紧急状态，实际上将承诺的选举推迟到明年，声称这是稳定所必需的。</p><p>据监测逮捕和伤亡情况的非营利组织政治犯援助协会称，自政变以来已有 3,800 多人被杀， <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/hundreds-detained-by-myanmar-military-simply-disappearwhere-is-my-mom-11619265604?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">近 20,000 人仍被拘留</a>。政治家、艺术家、记者和其他人仍在狱中。</p><p>写信给费利斯·所罗门 (Feliz Solomon)： <a href="mailto:feliz.solomon@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">feliz.solomon@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Tue, 01 Aug 2023 10:14:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/myanmars-aung-san-suu-kyi-serving-33-year-sentence-gets-surprise-partial-pardon-74eae973</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/myanmars-aung-san-suu-kyi-serving-33-year-sentence-gets-surprise-partial-pardon-74eae973<author><![CDATA[Feliz Solomon]]></author><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>国家/公共安全</category><category>叛乱</category><category>犯罪/法律诉讼</category><category>欺诈罪</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>军事行动</category><category>选举</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>昂山素季</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>国家的</category><category>公安</category><category>叛乱</category><category>犯罪</category><category>合法举动</category><category>欺诈罪</category><category>政治</category><category>国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>军事行动</category><category>选举</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[In Ukraine, a Surge in Amputations Reveals the Human Cost of Russia’s War]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>自战争开始以来，估计有数万人失去了肢体，这一数字在西方最近的武装冲突中从未出现过<figure><img src="https://images.wsj.net/im-824318/?width=1278&amp;size=1" alt="自与俄罗斯的战争开始以来，有 20,000 至 50,000 名乌克兰人失去了一条或多条肢体，鲁斯兰娜·达尼尔基娜 (Ruslana Danilkina) 就是其中之一。" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>自与俄罗斯的战争开始以来，有 20,000 至 50,000 名乌克兰人失去了一条或多条肢体，鲁斯兰娜·达尼尔基娜 (Ruslana Danilkina) 就是其中之一。弗拉达和康斯坦丁·利贝罗夫/LIBKOS<span>弗拉达和康斯坦丁·利贝罗夫/LIBKOS</span> </figcaption></figure><!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001097972"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001097972"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/bojan-pancevski" itemprop="url" rel="author">博扬·潘切夫斯基</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 8 月 1 日上午 6:08 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/in-ukraine-a-surge-in-amputations-reveals-the-human-cost-of-russias-war-d0bca320"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bigtophero
"></div><p>今年 2 月，19 岁的乌克兰士兵鲁斯兰娜·丹尼尔基娜 (Ruslana Danilkina) 在乌克兰东南部扎波罗热周围的前线附近遭到枪击。弹片将她的左腿从膝盖上方撕断。她紧紧抓住被切断的大腿骨，看着医护人员将她被切断的腿放进车里，然后将她送往医院。</p><p> “我手里拿着骨头……然后我意识到这就是结局，我的生活将不再一样，”丹尼尔基纳说。</p><p>根据假肢公司、医生和慈善机构此前未公开的估计，自战争爆发以来，已有 20,000 至 50,000 名乌克兰人失去一根或多根肢体，达尼尔基纳就是其中之一。</p><p>实际数字可能更高，因为患者接受手术后需要时间进行登记。有些人受伤几周或几个月后就被截肢。随着<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/ukraine-war-counteroffensive-frontlines-russia-add3e4e4?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">基辅的反攻正在进行</a>，战争可能会进入<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/ukraines-lack-of-weaponry-and-training-risks-stalemate-in-fight-with-russia-f51ecf9?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">更加残酷的阶段</a>。</p><p>相比之下，第一次世界大战期间，约有 67,000 名德国人和 41,000 名英国人不得不接受截肢手术，当时这种手术往往是唯一可以避免死亡的方法。参与阿富汗和伊拉克战争的美国退伍军人不到 2000 名接受了截肢手术。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          wrap
"><figure class="media-object-image img-wrap"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="639" height="426" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-826535?width=639&amp;height=426" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">奥托博克董事长 Hans Georg Näder 与该公司的顶级 Genium 假腿。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：奥托博克</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>乌克兰政府没有立即回应对这些数据发表评论的请求。基辅对准确的伤亡统计数据保密，以免民众士气低落。但即使作为粗略估计，这个数字也揭示了俄罗斯长达 17 个月的猛攻所造成的惊人的人员伤亡——随着一代残疾人重返平民生活，这一损失将持续数十年。</p><p>德国奥托博克是世界上最大的假肢制造商，该公司正在与基辅合作帮助截肢者，根据政府和医疗合作伙伴的数据估计截肢者人数约为 50,000 人。总部位于基辅的慈善机构胡普基金会估计，战争造成的重伤人数为 20 万人。据该基金会称，大约 10% 的严重伤害通常需要截肢。</p><p>这些数字反映了俄罗斯发动战争的方式，大量使用地雷和大炮、导弹和无人机袭击士兵和平民。</p><p> “我的祖父于 1919 年创立了我们公司，旨在帮助......从第一次世界大战中因炮火受伤返回的德国士兵，他们失去了手臂、腿或视力 - 这正是我们在乌克兰看到的情况，”奥托博克董事长 Hans Georg Näder 说道。</p><p>丹尼尔基纳在位于西部城市利沃夫的慈善基金会 Superhumans 的帮助下，接受了奥托博克的假肢手术，之前接受了五次手术。</p><p>她已经 20 岁了，一直在社交媒体上用“Unbreakable Rusya”这个昵称记录自己的康复情况。周一，她收到了奥托博克与美国军方合作开发的一款名为 Genium X3 的更复杂的腿，可以让用户轻松爬楼梯，甚至倒退行走。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-824324?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">丹尼尔基纳在乌克兰东南部前线附近受伤。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：Vlada 和 Konstantyn Liberov/LIBKOS</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>丹尼斯·克雷文科 (Denys Kryvenko) 是一名来自乌克兰中部克罗皮夫尼茨基 (Kropyvnytskiy) 的 24 岁前钢铁工人，去年应征入伍，在一月份的巴赫穆特战役中失去了双腿和左臂。受伤前，他身高 6 英尺 1 英寸，但现在用假腿站立时身高为 5 英尺 6 英寸。</p><p>克雷文科和丹尼尔基纳现在都与超人一起帮助其他截肢者。他们的社交网络激进主义和媒体形象使他们成为乌克兰苦难和恢复力的象征。</p><p>制造足够的假肢并不是主要的挑战，其中一些假肢的成本超过 50,000 欧元，相当于 55,000 美元左右：更大的瓶颈是护理截肢者的专家人员，每个人都需要量身定制的假肢，Näder 说。基辅为每位军事截肢者支付高达 20,000 欧元的费用，但平民往往难以负担治疗费用。奥托博克为乌克兰人提供折扣，并为那里的医生和技术人员提供免费培训。尽管如此，许多患者仍必须依靠慈善机构来获得假肢。</p><p>去年俄罗斯入侵之前，乌克兰每年有数千人截肢，但据乌克兰医生和专科诊所称，其医疗保健系统现在已经不堪重负，许多患者等待新肢体需要一年多的时间。医疗康复中心网络 Unbroken 的高管奥列克桑德·科布扎列夫 (Oleksandr Kobzarev) 表示，去年仅利沃夫的医生就进行了 53,000 多例手术。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="867" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-826537?width=700&amp;height=867" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">失去双腿和一条手臂的乌克兰士兵丹尼斯·克雷文科在乌克兰文尼察的一家军医院接受手术后与一名军医在一起。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：丹尼斯·克里文科</p></figcaption></figure></div><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="704" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-826533?width=700&amp;height=704" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">丹尼斯·克雷文科 (Denys Kryvenko) 与鲁斯兰娜·丹尼尔基娜 (Ruslana Danilkina) 在乌克兰超人康复中心接受治疗。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：丹尼斯·克里文科</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>Superhumans 首席执行官奥尔加·鲁德涅娃 (Olga Rudneva) 表示，她的基金会每月只能接纳大约 50 名截肢者。她估计自去年以来截肢者人数至少有 20,000 人。</p><p> Rudneva 说，患者最晚应该在截肢后 90 天获得新肢体，以避免萎缩和其他问题，但许多人已经等待了一年多。她说，截肢者中的幼儿尤其难以照顾，因为他们成年后必须更换多个假肢。</p><p> 7 岁的奥莱克桑德拉·帕斯卡尔 (Oleksandra Paskal) 在 2022 年 5 月敖德萨附近的一次俄罗斯导弹袭击中失去了一条腿。她的母亲玛丽亚在爆炸中部分丧失了听力，她说她的女儿晚上会被失去的肢体的幻痛惊醒，这是一种常见的神经疾病截肢者的情况。</p><p> Jennifer Ernst 博士是德国汉诺威大学医院创新截肢医学科主任，专门从事涉及神经与假肢连接的仿生手术。她最近为一名士兵进行了手术，这名士兵在一次袭击中失去了双腿，导致他的整个部队丧生。</p><p>与许多在严重创伤后撤离到国外的乌克兰患者一样，这名士兵也受到了抗生素耐药性细菌感染，迫使恩斯特切除了重要的腿部组织。尽管取得了成功——一名患者的手臂被 3D 打印的骨植入物救活了——但她表示，大多数患者由于严重感染而不得不截肢。</p><p>去年，她的诊所收治了一名 16 岁男孩，他在一枚俄罗斯导弹击中基辅地铁站时失去了一只手臂。爆炸杀死了他的妹妹，但他们的母亲只受了轻伤。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="525" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-824387?width=700&amp;height=525" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> 2022 年 5 月，7 岁的奥莱克桑德拉·帕斯卡尔 (Oleksandra Paskal) 在敖德萨附近的一次俄罗斯导弹袭击中失去了一条腿。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：敖德萨市议会</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>根据乌克兰军方与美国军医小组分享的估计，在距离前线约 3 英里范围内的 100 名受伤士兵中，36% 的伤势非常严重，而所有部署的士兵中有 5% 至 10% 死亡。相比之下，部署在最近冲突中的美军中只有1.3%至2%在行动中死亡。</p><p>训练乌克兰军医的前军外科医生组成的全球外科和医疗支持小组负责人亚伦·爱泼斯坦博士说，自二战以来，西方军外科医生还没有见过如此规模的伤害。</p><p>虽然大炮和导弹是冲突初期造成截肢的主要原因，但现在伤亡最严重的一些是来自 600 英里前线沿线埋设的地雷。私人 KSM 诊所的医疗主任 Kostyantyn Mylytsya 博士说，每天有 40 至 80 名受伤患者到扎波罗热市的医院报案，其中包括来自约 25 英里外前线的截肢者。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=B4EEDAEB-204A-4D35-A945-2EA739618C35&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fin-ukraine-a-surge-in-amputations-reveals-the-human-cost-of-russias-war-d0bca320&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption">风暴之影导弹使乌克兰的反攻行动能够打击前线后方的俄罗斯目标。 《华尔街日报》探讨了这种武器的工作原理以及它为何迫使莫斯科重新考虑其后勤保障。照片插图：Nayon Cho<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div><p>Mylytsya 在战前专注于整容手术。现在他的诊所为截肢者提供治疗和康复服务。他说，“乌克兰的每个城镇都需要这样的中心；他们一定和牙医一样普遍。”</p><p>一名在乌克兰武装部队服役的前英国伞兵在六月份的一次地雷爆炸中失去了一只脚。去年四月，即志愿参战一个月后，他曾受过伤，当时一枚俄罗斯巡航导弹击中了他所在部队的总部。他在乌克兰和英国的医院住了五个月，但尽快返回了南部前线。</p><div class="media-object scope-web
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4>分享你的意见</h4><p><em>战争将对乌克兰人产生什么长期影响？加入下面的对话。</em></p></div></div><p>六月，他的部队对俄罗斯军队发动了夜间突袭，但遭受了毁灭性的损失。他的队伍在一所废弃学校的地下室里躲了一夜，然后再次发动袭击。他们驶过被摧毁的西部豹坦克、悍马车和布拉德利步兵战车。战友的断肢散落在地上。</p><p>士兵们用断棍敲击前进的道路，以探测隐藏的地雷。当这位 28 岁的男子在俄罗斯废弃战壕附近架设机枪时，踩到了一枚杀伤人员地雷。</p><p> “我尖叫着朝行进方向摔倒，很幸运没有撞到另一个地雷，”他说。</p><p>他被送往野战医院，医生保住了他的腿，但切断了他的大部分左脚。他说，袭击发生后，他所在单位的许多人都住院了。陪同他们的士兵大部分都死了。</p><p>现在，在美国等待治疗的他说，他打算回到自己的团，即使只是作为一名教官。</p><p> “这场战争是可怕的，现在我也成了残废……但我不后悔，”他说。</p><p>写信给博扬·潘切夫斯基（Bojan Pancevski）： <a href="mailto:bojan.pancevski@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">bojan.pancevski@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Tue, 01 Aug 2023 10:08:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/in-ukraine-a-surge-in-amputations-reveals-the- human-cost-of-Russias-war-d0bca320</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/in-ukraine-a-surge-in-amputations-reveals-the- human-cost-of-Russias-war-d0bca320<author><![CDATA[Bojan Pancevski]]></author><category>专有的</category><category>乌克兰</category><category>医疗设备/用品</category><category>医疗保健/生命科学</category><category>医疗器械/仪器</category><category>骨科/假肢植入物/装置</category><category>诊断/治疗设备</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>国家/公共安全</category><category>健康</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>医疗/程序</category><category>军事行动</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>国家的</category><category>公安</category><category>健康</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>医疗</category><category>程序</category><category>军事行动</category><category>医用器材</category><category>补给品</category><category>卫生保健</category><category>生命科学</category><category>医疗设备</category><category>仪器</category><category>骨科的</category><category>假体植入物</category><category>设备</category><category>诊断</category><category>治疗装置</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Countries Raid Each Others’ Health Systems in Global Battle for Nurses]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>医疗人员的短缺导致世界各地的偷猎活动猖獗，激怒了较贫穷的国家；在澳大利亚骑自行车上班<figure><img src="https://images.wsj.net/im-826463/?width=1278&amp;size=1" alt="性健康医生哈迪普·康 (Hardeep Kang) 医生在澳大利亚凯恩斯的新工作中，在一家英国招聘机构与她接洽后，她搬到了那里。" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>性健康医生哈迪普·康 (Hardeep Kang) 医生在澳大利亚凯恩斯的新工作中，在一家英国招聘机构与她接洽后，她搬到了那里。 Brian Cassey for The Wall Street Journal <span>Brian Cassey for The Wall Street Journal</span> </figcaption></figure><!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001093125"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001093125"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/stuart-condie" itemprop="url" rel="author">Stuart Condie</a></span> and <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/gabriele-steinhauser" itemprop="url" rel="author">Gabriele Steinhauser</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> Aug. 1, 2023 12:01 am ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/countries-raid-each-others-health-systems-in-global-battle-for-nurses-b2de0429"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bigtophero
"></div><p> A global shortage of healthcare workers is setting off a bruising <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/high-pay-for-covid-19-nurses-leads-to-shortages-at-some-hospitals-11630253483?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">worldwide battle for talent</a> , as rich countries raid other nations&#39; medical systems for staff to care for their aging populations.</p><p> The competition has helped countries such as the US and Australia replace some nurses who quit in record numbers during the height of the Covid-19 pandemic. But it is also leaving hospitals in developing countries and some wealthier nations such as the UK worse off, as they lose staff to countries offering bigger paychecks.</p><p> Australia has been one of the most aggressive poachers, with offers of special bonuses and fast-tracked visas. An Australian advertising campaign in the British Isles this past winter featured workers with sunshine streaming through windows behind them. The campaign coincided with British nurses <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-k-nurses-stage-biggest-ever-strike-as-health-system-strains-11671121289?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">going on strike</a> over pay, long hours and other concerns.</p><p> “You can surf in the early mornings, go fly fishing on weekends, take photography classes, write novels, or sell preserves at the farmers&#39; markets,” stated an ad in the British Medical Journal, an industry magazine, for an emergency-medicine registrar job.</p><div class="media-object scope-web,mobileapps
          wrap
"></div><p> The health department in Australia&#39;s Tasmania state, which placed the ad, said that like other local authorities it is looking to many countries including the UK for overseas workers.</p><p> The battle is part of <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-worlds-biggest-economies-cautiously-open-their-doors-to-more-foreign-workers-664c3549?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">a global resurgence in migration</a> that is reshaping the world economy this year. As borders have reopened since the worst of the pandemic, countries have been welcoming foreign workers in selected industries to address labor shortfalls, helping push migration to record levels.</p><p> Douglas Chikobvu, a nurse at Gweru Provincial Hospital in Zimbabwe, said he has watched about a dozen nurses from his surgical ward move to take jobs abroad in recent years.</p><p> Chikobvu, who is secretary-general of the Zimbabwe Professional Nurses Union, said that in some hospitals one nurse sometimes ends up looking after 25 or 30 patients during a shift, instead of a more reasonable level of 10. Doctors are being forced to cancel procedures because they don&#39;t have enough staff.</p><p> Zimbabwe&#39;s vice president, Constantino Chiwenga,</p> who is also the health minister, in April threatened that his country would pass a new law that would criminalize the active recruitment of Zimbabwe&#39;s healthcare workers.<p></p><p> Data released by the UK government this year showed that the UK alone issued 17,421 health- and care-worker visas to Zimbabwe nationals in the 12 months to March 31—almost six times as many as in the previous 12 months. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-826697?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Nurse Douglas Chikobvu says nurses have left Zimbabwe to take jobs abroad.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Cynthia R Matonhodze for The Wall Street Journal </p></figcaption></figure></div><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-826789?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Nurses demonstrated outside a Zimbabwe hospital in June as they pushed for better pay.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: aaron ufumeli/Shutterstock</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> Speaking at an event on human trafficking in April, Chiwenga referred to the recruitment of developing-world medical staff as a “crime against humanity.”</p><p> “If people die in hospitals because there are no nurses and doctors—and somebody who has been so irresponsible for not training their own nationals, but wanting poor countries to train for them—it&#39;s a crime that must be taken seriously,” he said.</p><p> The World Health Organization in March this year published a list of 55 countries—37 of them in Africa—with the most pressing health-workforce challenges. These countries on average have just 15 health workers per 10,000 people, compared with 148 per 10,000 in high-income countries.</p><p> The WHO has asked its members not to actively recruit doctors and nurses from these 55 nations without first sealing bilateral agreements to support the countries where they are recruiting. Such support could include financing the training of new staff or plans for health workers to return to their country of origin after a number of years.</p><p> For wealthier countries, luring medical staff from abroad is attractive because it can take years to train nurses and doctors. Between 2020 and 2021, <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/nurse-shortage-hospitals-hiring-gig-economy-dc94bdb2?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">the US lost more than 100,000 nurses</a> , the largest decline on record, a study in the journal Health Affairs showed.</p><p> Since the height of the pandemic, hospitals have struggled to rebuild normal staffing levels and morale. Improved salaries and working conditions <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/nurses-flock-back-to-hospitals-after-leaving-in-the-pandemic-4f94b591?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">have since drawn some workers back</a> , but shortages remain. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-826724?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Douglas Chikobvu heads to work at Gweru Provincial Hospital in Zimbabwe.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Cynthia R Matonhodze for The Wall Street Journal </p></figcaption></figure></div><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-826698?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Douglas Chikobvu, hanging up his uniform at his home, says that at some hospitals in Zimbabwe a single nurse can look after 25 or 30 patients during a shift.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Cynthia R Matonhodze for The Wall Street Journal</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> In Australia, the number of advertised vacancies for health professionals more than doubled from early 2020 to August 2022 and remained close to that historic peak nine months later, according to the most recent data from the Australian Bureau of Statistics.</p><p> The country granted 4,950 visas to healthcare workers over the nine months through March 2023, according to data from the Australian Department of Home Affairs. That number is up 48% from a year earlier—yet the country is still facing nursing shortages, officials say.</p><p> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/AU/XASX/RHC" class="">Ramsay Health Care</a> <span class="company-name-type">,</span> which owns more than 500 hospitals and clinics in Australia and 10 other countries, recently said a lack of skilled workers continues to limit its ability to treat patients. It is looking overseas for staff, it said.</p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"></div><p> Dr. Hardeep Kang, a sexual-health physician, was working in northern Britain when she was approached by a recruitment agency to see whether she would be interested in a move to Australia. She now works in Cairns, a city in northern Australia known as a gateway to the Great Barrier Reef, after migrating in November.</p><p> Kang said she now earns about $56,000 more a year than in the UK, in part because of a supplement offered by the state government to sweeten roles outside major cities. Her daily commute involves riding a bicycle along the oceanfront.</p><p> Rebekah Daly, a radiologist who moved to Australia in January from Ireland, said that almost a quarter of her co-workers back home had quit to travel or work overseas now that Covid-related travel restrictions had been lifted, adding to the workload of those left behind. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="909" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-826464?width=1260&amp;height=909" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> A bicycle is part of Dr. Hardeep Kang&#39;s daily commute in Australia.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Brian Cassey for The Wall Street Journal </p></figcaption></figure></div><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="905" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-826737?width=1260&amp;height=905" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> She says that she now earns about $56,000 more a year in Australia than in the UK</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Brian Cassey for The Wall Street Journal</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> The UK has introduced a new visa for healthcare workers with less onerous provisions than those for other skilled workers. It issued 101,570 visas to health and care workers in the 12 months ended March 31, nearly three times as many as during the previous year, with most recruits coming from India, Nigeria and Zimbabwe, according to government data.</p><p> After the publication of the WHO list, the UK government said health and social care organizations wouldn&#39;t actively recruit from nations flagged by the agency, but there is nothing that stops health workers from these countries from applying for open posts.</p><p> Ireland—which depended heavily on overseas health workers before the pandemic—last year relaxed employment restrictions for non-European doctors already in the country as part of an effort to keep them.</p><p> More than 70 countries have introduced laws in recent years to make it easier to hire health workers from abroad, according to the WHO. Other rich countries like Germany have made the recruitment of healthcare workers part of high-level trips to countries such as Ghana, Brazil and Albania.</p><p> In the US, <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/green-card-backlog-fuels-shortage-of-nurses-at-hospitals-nursing-homes-4f0b0e44?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">recruiting nurses from abroad effectively stopped</a> because the type of green card that healthcare institutions use to hire nurses became so oversubscribed that the State Department stopped processing applications.截至 9 月份的过去两个财年，包括注册护士和职业护士在内的海外医疗工作者的签证筛查请求均增长了 40% 以上。</p><div class="media-object scope-web
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4>分享你的意见</h4><p><em>How should the global healthcare shortage problem be addressed?加入下面的对话。</em></p></div></div><p> Some developing countries are pushing back by making it more difficult for health workers to emigrate.</p><p> The Philippines, which has long lost many of its healthcare workers to the US, <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/coronavirus-heightens-global-struggle-for-migrant-nurses-11588161393?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">imposed a temporary ban on more leaving</a> during the pandemic. It continues to cap the number who can work overseas, even though doing so deprives the country of much-needed income from remittances.</p><p> Nigerian lawmakers are considering a bill that would require doctors to work at home for at least five years before they are allowed to emigrate.</p><p> Zimbabwe&#39;s Health Service Commission, which oversees staffing there, says it needs 81,517 healthcare workers to meet population needs, but as of last September it had only 74,298.</p><p> Chikobvu, the nurse at Gweru Provincial Hospital in Zimbabwe, said he and his colleagues share ads for jobs in countries such as the US and the UK in dedicated WhatsApp groups.</p><p> Despite seeing the effects of the medical brain drain in his country, Chikobvu is currently applying for nursing jobs in the US and opposes restrictions on rich countries hiring nurses from poor ones.</p><p> He said his monthly income of about $425 isn&#39;t enough to pay for his family&#39;s food and healthcare and cover school fees for his four children. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-826712?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Douglas Chikobvu with his daughter in Zimbabwe. The secretary-general of a nurses union, he says that he is currently applying for nursing jobs in the US</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Cynthia R Matonhodze for The Wall Street Journal</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> Write to Stuart Condie at <a href="mailto:stuart.condie@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">stuart.condie@wsj.com</a> and Gabriele Steinhauser at <a href="mailto:Gabriele.Steinhauser@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">gabriele.steinhauser@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Tue, 01 Aug 2023 04:01:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/countries-raid-each-others-health-systems-in-global-battle-for-nurses-b2de0429</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/countries-raid-each-others-health-systems-in-global-battle-for-nurses-b2de0429<author><![CDATA[Stuart CondieGabriele Steinhauser]]></author><category>华尔街日报</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>犯罪/法律诉讼</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category> Ramsay Health Care</category><category> RHC.AU</category><category> AU:RHC</category><category> Douglas Chikobvu</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>犯罪</category><category>合法举动</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Niger Coup Leaders Detain Ministers, Party Officials]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> Arrests might complicate diplomacy to resolve crisis in counterterrorism ally as Russia&#39;s African allies back junta <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001098397"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-826728?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Police officers on the sidelines of a march in support of the coup plotters in Niamey, Niger&#39;s capital.</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：Djibo Issifou/Zuma Press </p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001098397"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/benoit-faucon" itemprop="url" rel="author">Benoit Faucon</a></span> and <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/gabriele-steinhauser" itemprop="url" rel="author">Gabriele Steinhauser</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> Updated July 31, 2023 6:27 pm ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/niger-coup-leaders-detain-ministers-party-officials-6ba1efa1"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p> Coup leaders in Niger on Monday arrested several ministers and senior members of the party of detained President Mohamed Bazoum, dealing a blow to efforts by African nations <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/west-african-leaders-threaten-force-against-niger-plotters-e046fae7?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">to find a diplomatic solution</a> to the <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/niger-general-declares-himself-leader-as-russian-mercenary-hails-coup-d47efa68?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">crisis that has shaken</a> one of the US&#39;s main counterterrorism allies as Russia&#39;s African allies declared their support for the junta.</p><p> Among those arrested were oil minister Mahamane Sani Mahamadou —the son of Bazoum&#39;s predecessor, Mahamadou Issoufou —and Mining Minister Ousseini Hadizatou as well as Foumakoye Gado, president of the executive committee of the Nigerien Party for Democracy and Socialism, said people familiar with the arrests.</p><p>知情人士称，该国内政部长、国防部长和交通部长上周被捕。</p><p> “逮捕的目的是斩首[NPDS]，以避免组织大规模抗议活动，”巴祖姆政党的一名高级成员说。 “他们还想在军事干预时将他们用作人质。”</p><p> The arrests are bound to complicate efforts by the African leaders—supported by Washington and Niger&#39;s former colonial power France—to restore Bazoum to power. At stake is how much the US can continue its military involvement in Niger, a key American hub for counterterrorism operations and drone flights between Libya, Mali and Nigeria.</p><p> On Monday, the US State Department said that it didn&#39;t believe last week&#39;s coup had succeeded yet. Were the State Department to determine a coup successfully took place, US laws would restrict American defense aid to Niger. The US has spent more than $500 million equipping and training Niger&#39;s military since 2012, and the country hosts American commandos who have advised Nigerien special forces during combat missions against local affiliates of al Qaeda and Islamic State.目前约有1100名美军驻扎在尼日尔。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=9B8EB2F8-7751-46ED-8D36-E964233A2505&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fniger-coup-leaders-detain-ministers-party-officials-6ba1efa1&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption">国务卿安东尼·布林肯周六表示，尼日尔的军事政变危及了美国价值数亿美元的援助和安全支持。欧盟还暂停了与尼日尔的安全合作和财政支持。照片：达伦·英格兰/Shutterstock<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div><p>Neighboring Nigeria and other West African countries are considering using military force to return the president to power. A senior State Department official declined to say whether the US supported an intervention by the African nations, saying it&#39;s a tricky question in part because an attack on Niger&#39;s presidential guard could endanger Bazoum.</p><p> At an emergency summit on Sunday, leaders from the Economic Community of West African States said they would give Niger&#39;s military junta, which is led by Gen. Omar Tchiani, the head of the presidential guards, one week to back down.如果做不到这一点，该组织（西非经共体）的领导人表示，他们将采取更有力的措施，包括可能的军事干预，以使巴祖姆重新掌权。</p><p>西非领导人还宣布了一系列痛苦的金融和贸易制裁，包括暂停向尼日尔出售电力和燃料，并冻结该国在地区央行的储备。</p><p> But the bloc&#39;s decision is facing opposition from other military leaders in the region who also came to power through coups and are now siding with Russia. In a joint statement late Monday, Burkina Faso and Mali, which are led respectively by Capt. Ibrahim Traore and Col. Assimi Goïta, said they had agreed to support the Niger junta. They said they would assist the coup plotters in Niamey if they were attacked. “Any military intervention against Niger will be considered as a declaration of war against Burkina Faso and Mali,” their joint statement said.</p><p> On Saturday, the European Union and France said they had suspended financial support for Niger&#39;s government, amounting to several hundred million dollars a year, while US Secretary of State Antony Blinken warned that US assistance to the country <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/blinken-says-u-s-aid-to-niger-in-jeopardy-following-coup-766a0156?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">was in jeopardy</a> .</p><p>法国官员周一表示，他们希望共同的经济和政治压力能够说服尼日尔武装部队放弃支持尼日尔总统卫队及其领导人奇亚尼领导的叛乱。</p><p>尼日尔拥有一个军事领导的政府，对尼日利亚等强大的西非国家以及美国和欧洲构成了巨大风险，尼日利亚与尼日尔有着约 1,000 英里的边界。三人都与巴祖姆政府和尼日尔军方密切合作，打击撒哈拉以南半干旱地带萨赫勒地区的伊斯兰武装分子。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="571" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-826730?width=700&amp;height=571" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> An image from the Facebook page of the president of Chad shows Chad&#39;s transitional president, Mahamat Deby, meeting Sunday with former Niger President Mahamadou Issoufou in Niger&#39;s capital.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Agence France-Presse/Getty Images</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>欧盟还依靠尼日尔阻止西非移民进入利比亚并从那里进入欧洲。</p><p>美国和欧洲官员担心军政府可能会寻求与莫斯科建立密切关系，就像尼日尔的几个邻国，包括马里和布基纳法索，在政变废黜民选总统后所做的那样。</p><p> Kremlin spokesman Dmitry Peskov on Monday called for “the rapid restoration of the rule of law in the country and for restraint from all parties so that this doesn&#39;t result in human casualties.”</p><p> In one round of shuttle diplomacy that didn&#39;t appear to yield immediate results,</p> Mahamat Deby, the transitional president of Chad, met with Tchiani, the leader of Niger&#39;s military junta, as well as Bazoum in Niamey, Niger&#39;s capital, on Sunday.<p></p><p>乍得政府表示，代比访问的目的是“不惜一切代价避免公开冲突和国家孤立”。它还警告说，如果危机持续下去，萨赫勒地区的恐怖组织将从中受益。</p><p> <em>—Noemie Bisserbe and Will Mauldin</em> <em>contributed to this article.</em></p><p> Write to Benoit Faucon at <a href="mailto:benoit.faucon@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">benoit.faucon@wsj.com</a> and Gabriele Steinhauser at <a href="mailto:Gabriele.Steinhauser@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">Gabriele.Steinhauser@wsj.com</a></p><p id="correction" class="correction"><strong>更正和放大</strong><br>Benoit Faucon and Gabriele Steinhauser reported this article. An earlier version incorrectly listed Drew Hinshaw in the byline and excluded Gabriele Steinhauser. Separately, Foumakoye Gado is president of the executive committee of the Nigerien Party for Democracy and Socialism. An earlier version of this article incorrectly spelled his name Fourmakoye Gado. (Corrected on July 31)</p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Mon, 31 Jul 2023 22:27:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/niger-coup-leaders-detain-ministers-party-officials-6ba1efa1</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/niger-coup-leaders-detain-ministers-party-officials-6ba1efa1<author><![CDATA[Benoit FauconGabriele Steinhauser]]></author><category>企业犯罪/法律诉讼</category><category>企业/行业新闻</category><category>法律诉讼 - 高管</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>内乱</category><category>国家/公共安全</category><category>社会/社区</category><category>Armed Rebellion</category><category>犯罪/法律诉讼</category><category>武装部队</category><category>国际关系</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>社会问题</category><category>军事行动</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>穆罕默德·巴祖姆</category><category>企业犯罪</category><category>合法举动</category><category>公司的</category><category>行业新闻</category><category>法律诉讼 - 高管</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>内乱</category><category>国家的</category><category>公安</category><category>社会</category><category>社区</category><category>armed rebellion</category><category>犯罪</category><category>armed forces</category><category>国际关系</category><category>政治</category><category>国内政治</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>社会问题</category><category>军事行动</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Real-Estate Deal Gone Bad Hits Popular Crowd Funder]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> CrowdStreet 通过向小投资者承诺巨额回报筹集了 40 亿美元，但许多交易令人失望<figure><img src="https://images.wsj.net/im-825172/?width=1278&amp;size=1" alt="涉及亚特兰大金融中心的交易是 CrowdStreet 有史以来规模最大的交易之一。" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>涉及亚特兰大金融中心的交易是 CrowdStreet 有史以来规模最大的交易之一。安德烈·珍妮/阿拉米<span>安德烈·珍妮/阿拉米</span></figcaption></figure><!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001091011"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001091011"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline">作者： <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/shane-shifflett" itemprop="url" rel="author">肖恩·希夫莱特</a></span>和<span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/ben-foldy" itemprop="url" rel="author">本·福迪</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">更新于 2023 年 7 月 31 日下午 6:01（东部时间） </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/missing-millions-and-a-rabbinical-arbitrator-real-estate-deal-gone-bad-hits-popular-crowd-funder-3555314f"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bigtophero
"></div><p>承诺让小投资者参与大型房地产项目的最大平台之一错过了危险信号，并将资金注入捏造过去的公司。现在，该公司面临着交易失败的问题，6300 万美元的<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/atlantas-record-62-million-crowdfunding-deal-raises-red-flags-with-some-investors-11661266801?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">客户现金</a>失踪。</p><p> CrowdStreet 通过宣扬丰厚回报为房地产开发商筹集了 40 亿美元，但许多交易都未能实现。</p><p>周一这篇报道发表后，CrowdStreet 表示将更换首席执行官。</p><p>失败的交易涉及一家名为南丁格尔地产（Nightingale Properties）的房地产开发商，该公司筹集资金购买亚特兰大和迈阿密的办公楼。在本月提交的破产申请中，新任命的项目首席重组官声称，这些建筑从未被购买，除了 127,000 美元之外，投资者的资金全部转移到其他账户，其中一些账户属于南丁格尔首席执行官。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><img width="600" height="1000" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-825518?width=600" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p>尽管存在一些潜在的危险信号，CrowdStreet 仍在推广 Nightingale 产品。该开发商在向投资者展示的业绩记录中省略了两笔糟糕交易的结果。交易运营协议中的仲裁条款规定，争议将由拉比法庭解决。</p><p>南丁格尔的律师及其首席执行官埃利·施瓦茨拒绝置评。被替换的 CrowdStreet 首席执行官托雷·斯蒂恩 (Tore Steen) 上周拒绝回答他的公司是否对丢失的资金负有任何责任，他表示，“CrowdStreet 没有在这里实施欺诈行为。” The RealDeal 早些时候报道了斯蒂恩的离职。</p><p> CrowdStreet 是小型投资者联合购买办公楼、酒店和其他类型商业房地产的多个平台中最大的平台之一。开发商通过网络广播向投资者进行推介，同时 CrowdStreet 代表介入宣布“立即投资”按钮何时被激活。</p><p>开发商支付费用来宣传他们的交易，投资者可以以低至 25,000 美元的价格购买少量股权。超过 770 笔交易的赞助商已在该平台上筹集了超过 40 亿美元。<br><br> 《华尔街日报》对 104 笔已完成的交易以及其他已中止或仍在进行中的交易进行的审查发现，许多交易未能达到销售宣传中建议的回报。当开发商资金短缺时，他们会要求投资者支付更多现金，否则将面临失去投资的风险。据美国证券交易委员会和司法部称，CrowdStreet 还帮助一家向投资者谎报业绩记录的公司筹集现金，该公司首席执行官后来因融资欺诈被判入狱。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=88CDF171-D046-4FD4-A4BB-72130DCCB4C6&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fmissing-millions-and-a-rabbinical-arbitrator-real-estate-deal-gone-bad-hits-popular-crowd-funder-3555314f&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption">由于住房供应短缺，开发商正在将更多空置办公室改造成公寓。但并非所有建筑物都适合重复利用，尽管美国各地有超过 10 亿平方英尺的办公空间闲置 图片插图：Amber Bragdon<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div><p>《华尔街日报》分析了该公司从 2013 年到 2022 年 8 月发布的 104 笔已完成的财产出售或投资者赎回交易的预期和实现回报数据。</p><p> 《华尔街日报》分析发现，CrowdStreet 平台上推广的投资中有一半以上未能达到目标回报。据《华尔街日报》分析，截至今年 7 月，数百名 CrowdStreet 用户在 19 笔表现不佳的交易中损失了约 3400 万美元。其中十几笔交易损失了近 100% 的投资者资金。</p><p> CrowdStreet 也举办了成功的交易。超过 20 笔交易的回报率超出预期至少 10 个百分点。还有数百人仍然悬而未决。投资者通常需要至少三年的时间才能实现投资回报。</p><p>该平台的一位发言人表示，该公司看到的交易实现的回报高于或低于预期，并为投资者创造了 3.07 亿美元的利润。</p><p>由于供应短缺、价格上涨或利率上升，一些开发商遇到了意想不到的成本或低估了他们的现金需求。</p><p> 2020 年至 2021 年间，Fountain Residential Partners 在 CrowdStreet 上筹集了 4500 万美元，用于克莱姆森大学、阿肯色大学和路易斯安那州立大学的三个校外学生住房项目，其中一个需要大修，另一个基本上无法居住<strong>&nbsp;</strong>洪水发生后几个月。</p><p>由于成本超支，Fountain 向 CrowdStreet 投资者追加 1,240 万美元，并于 9 月份被告知预计将再筹集数百万美元。</p><p> “看来我们还需要 2000 万美元才能完成该项目，”Fountain 首席执行官布伦特·利特尔 (Brent Little) 在 9 月份的阿肯色州项目网络研讨会上说道。利特尔将超支归咎于疫情期间<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/sky-high-lumber-prices-are-back-11639842879?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">木材价格</a>上涨等材料价格。该公司几个月来都没有透露需要更多资金来完成修复，因为“我们认为这会引发不必要的恐慌，”他说。</p><p>利特尔拒绝发表评论。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="503" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-825194?width=700&amp;height=503" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> 2020 年至 2021 年间，为克莱姆森大学和其他学校的校外学生住宿项目筹集了数百万美元。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：肯·鲁纳德/美联社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>CrowdStreet 的营销材料对房地产回报做出了乐观的假设。在该公司运营的私人房地产投资信托基金的宣传中，该公司表示，从历史上看，较高的利率会增加房地产价值。格林街商业地产价格指数显示，随着利率上升，房产价值通常会下降，自美联储去年开始加息以来，房产价值已经下降了 15%。</p><p> 2018 年，MG Capital Management 向 CrowdStreet 投资者推出了一只新基金，该公司自称是“曼哈顿最大的无债务个人豪华房产业主兼管理者”。 CrowdStreet 的首席投资官当时谈到 MG 时表示：“我们专门与领先的赞助商合作提供商业房地产产品，以满足我们严格的市场要求。”<br><br> MG Capital 的发行材料称，该公司监管的两只基金在 10 年内的回报率是标准普尔 500 指数的四倍。该公司表示，新基金的投资者“100%免受损失”。 MG Capital 从 CrowdStreet 投资者那里筹集了 180 万美元，该基金筹集的资金总额为 3500 万美元。据 CrowdStreet 称，参与此次交易的 23 名投资者收回了约三分之一的资金。<br><br> 2021年，美国证券交易委员会和司法部指控MG Capital及其经理犯有证券欺诈罪。政府表示，MG Capital 的基金伪造报告以掩盖巨额损失，其之前的基金根本不存在。 MG Capital 首席执行官承认融资证券欺诈罪，被判处 60 个月监禁，MG Capital 与 SEC 达成和解。</p><p> Nightingale 收购亚特兰大金融中心的交易是 CrowdStreet 有史以来规模最大的交易之一。潜在投资者收到了 CrowdStreet 首席投资官发来的电子邮件，主题为：“100 亿美元的企业赞助商在热门市场带来了具有巨大潜力的奖杯资产。” Nightingale 从 654 名 CrowdStreet 投资者那里筹集了约 5400 万美元，用于在亚特兰大巴克海特社区建造一座闪闪发光的玻璃覆盖办公楼。开发商还为迈阿密的一座建筑筹集了约 800 万美元。</p><p> CrowdStreet 将南丁格尔评为最高级别的“企业”赞助商，表明其业务遍及全国，投资组合价值超过 50 亿美元。此次上市预计内部回报率为28.1%，是该平台项目中最高的。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-825196?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> MG Capital 将自己描述为曼哈顿最大的无债务个人豪华房产业主兼管理者。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：AMR ALFIKY/路透社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>去年夏天，路易斯安那州的神经科学家彼得·坎贝尔 (Peter Campbell) 在这笔交易中投入了 10 万美元，他说：“所有这些因素共同作用，引发了围绕这项投资的狂热。”<br><br> Nightingale 向 CrowdStreet 支付了使用其市场的费用，并计划在交易完成后向其支付超过 210 万美元。<br><br>去年夏天，《华尔街日报》报道称，一些投资者在发现南丁格尔遗漏了前一年向贷方损失一栋大楼以及拖欠投资者资料 2500 万美元后，对这项投资产生了不满。当时，CrowdStreet 的一位发言人表示，这些遗漏是良性的、无关紧要的，如果投资者愿意，他们可以退还资金。</p><p> CrowdStreet 的 Steen 在上周接受《华尔街日报》采访时表示，该公司在其流程中分析了未公开的交易，但认为违约或取消抵押品赎回权不应阻止开发商在该平台上上市。</p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"></div><p> CrowdStreet 允许投资者在 2 月份之前为该交易提供资金，但一些人表示，他们开始要求 CrowdStreet 和 Nightingale 退还资金。坎贝尔表示，他向南丁格尔公司高管发送了 11 封电子邮件并召开了电话会议，之后他的资金才于 6 月份返还。<br><br>丹尼斯·格卢什科夫从三月份开始要求他提供资金。 CrowdStreet 告诉他，Nightingale 会尊重退款请求，但第二天，Nightingale 在一封电子邮件中告诉他，“目前不考虑任何赎回”，因为它试图完成该建筑的交易。</p><p>格卢什科夫五月份被告知，他已被添加到即将赎回的名单中，但从未拿到钱。该公司持有投资者现金，并于 7 月 14 日在特拉华州根据美国破产法第 11 章申请破产保护。<br><br>当天晚些时候，被任命为该工具受托人的安娜·菲利普斯 (Anna Phillips) 告诉投资者，财务记录显示，在从投资者那里筹集资金后不久，数百万美元就已转移给施瓦茨及其关联公司。投资者的资金只剩下 127,000 美元。</p><div class="media-object scope-web
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4>分享你的意见</h4><p><em>您对 CrowdStreet 等众筹平台有何看法？加入下面的对话。</em></p></div></div><p>菲利普斯表示，交易存在“大量存在欺诈迹象的危险信号”，但她表示，她需要直接与施瓦茨交谈并收集更多事实，然后才能做出决定。<br><br>这笔钱并不像房地产交易中常见的那样存入托管账户。 CrowdStreet 从六月开始使用此类帐户。斯蒂恩表示，该公司也在改变其商业模式，不再是一个为投资者与试图筹集资金的公司牵线搭桥的市场。它将成为一家注册经纪交易商，就像大多数出售投资的公司一样。</p><p>格卢什科夫表示，CrowdStreet 很容易成为欺诈目标，他对 CrowdStreet 没有采取更多措施保护投资者现金感到震惊。</p><p> “如果你决定窃取 7000 万美元，我相信如果是高盛的，他们会三思而后行，”他说。 “当你的投资基础小而分散时，你就更容易想到，‘我要挪用这些资金，祝他们好运。’”</p><p>写信给 Shane Shifflett <a href="mailto:shane.shifflett@dowjones.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">（shane.shifflett@dowjones.com）</a>和 Ben Foldy（ <a href="mailto:ben.foldy@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">ben.foldy@wsj.com</a> ）</p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Mon, 31 Jul 2023 22:01:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/missing-millions-and-a-rabbinical-仲裁员-real-estate-deal-gone-bad-hits-popular-crowd-funder-3555314f</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/missing-millions-and-a-rabbinical-仲裁员-real-estate-deal-gone-bad-hits-popular-crowd-funder-3555314f<author><![CDATA[Shane ShifflettBen Foldy]]></author><category>华尔街日报财经</category><category>专有的</category><category>企业融资</category><category>企业/行业新闻</category><category>众筹</category><category>中小型企业</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>布伦特·利特尔</category><category>企业融资</category><category>公司的</category><category>行业新闻</category><category>众筹</category><category>小的</category><category>中型企业</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Muslim Nations Call on Sweden, Denmark to Ban Quran Burnings]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> Russia has been trying to drive a wedge between NATO partners as the diplomatic crisis builds <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001099056"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-826772?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Iranian demonstrators in Tehran earlier this month burned a Swedish flag to protest the burning of a Quran in Sweden.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Sobhan Farajvan/Zuma Press </p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001099056"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/sune-engel-rasmussen" itemprop="url" rel="author">Sune Engel Rasmussen</a></span> and <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/humza-jilani" itemprop="url" rel="author">Humza Jilani</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> July 31, 2023 3:48 pm ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/muslim-nations-call-on-sweden-denmark-to-ban-quran-burnings-ae94907"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p> LONDON—The world&#39;s largest grouping of Muslim nations demanded that Sweden and Denmark ban desecrations of the Quran, the latest stage in what is turning out to be a clash between the Scandinavian countries&#39; free-speech principles and the West&#39;s ability to build a broader coalition to counter Russian aggression following the invasion of Ukraine.</p><p> At an extraordinary summit, held virtually, the 57 members of the Organization of Islamic Cooperation said <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/swedish-embassy-in-iraq-set-on-fire-in-protest-against-planned-quran-burning-ed731d20?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">recent burnings of the Quran in Scandinavia</a> represented a “culture of hatred and racism, and a manifestation of Islamophobia,” according to a statement. While it stopped short of calling for a boycott of Danish and Swedish goods, the OIC demanded the “criminalization of such extremist provocative acts,” it said.</p><p> A wave of demonstrations has seen protesters in both Denmark and Sweden burn copies of the Quran outside the embassies of Muslim nations in recent days. The protests have been sparsely attended. In Sweden, several of the demonstrations were staged by an Iraqi refugee who had his application for residency denied.</p><p> But they have provoked uproar in parts of the Islamic world, opening a crack between the West and influential Muslim nations as Europe and the US look to build a wider alliance to minimize Russia&#39;s influence.</p><p> The incidents have prompted Stockholm and Copenhagen, both of which pride themselves on free speech as well as religious tolerance, to say they will probe ways to ban Quran desecrations. Both countries outlaw hate speech against specific individuals and groups but currently consider Quran burnings to be legal criticism of religion, though they have been at pains to distance themselves from the desecrations.</p><p> The crisis could complicate <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/sweden-races-to-secure-turkish-support-for-nato-bid-2452c14f?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">Sweden&#39;s bid to join the North Atlantic Treaty Organization</a> . After blocking Sweden&#39;s accession to NATO for more than a year, Turkey earlier in July said it would drop its opposition. Yet Turkish President Recep Tayyip Erdogan has said it is up to the country&#39;s parliament to approve the bid once it reconvenes in October, leaving open the possibility of further delays. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=60B96BB5-D1B4-4ED6-8F76-7CD927DBFA17&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fmuslim-nations-call-on-sweden-denmark-to-ban-quran-burnings-ae94907&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption"> Iraq&#39;s government expelled Sweden&#39;s ambassador on Thursday, hours after crowds set fire to the Swedish Embassy in Baghdad to protest a planned burning of a Quran in Stockholm. Sweden condemned the embassy attack as unacceptable. Photo: Ahmad Al-Rubaye/AFP/Getty Images<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div><p>Previous Quran burnings <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/turkeys-erdogan-threatens-to-block-swedens-nato-entrance-over-quran-burning-11674498389?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">hardened Turkey&#39;s opposition to Sweden&#39;s membership</a> , according to Swedish officials. In January, following a Quran burning in Stockholm, Ankara canceled a visit by the Swedish foreign minister to discuss the NATO accession.</p><p> Sweden last week accused Russia of orchestrating disinformation aimed at hurting its NATO campaign by implying that Stockholm supported Quran burnings.</p><p> “We can see how Russia-backed actors are amplifying incorrect statements such as that the Swedish state is behind the desecration of holy scriptures,” Swedish Minister for Civil Defense Carl-Oskar Bohlin said. “That is, naturally, completely false.”</p><p> Russia, which has observer status in the OIC, has sought to drive a wedge between Muslim majority nations and the West, casting itself as a champion of multifaith tolerance.</p><p> The Quran “is sacred for Muslims, and should be sacred for others,” President <a href="https://www.wsj.com/topics/person/vladimir-putin?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">Vladimir Putin</a> said during a visit in June to the Muslim majority Russian republic of Dagestan, in comments broadcast on Turkish state television. “We know that in other countries they act differently. They do not respect the religious feelings of people, and they also say that this is not a crime. In our country, this is a crime.”</p><p> In Lebanon, a Russian-Lebanese cooperation organization has placed billboards depicting Putin holding the Quran, referring to him as the “guardian and defender of religions,” according to Russian state media.</p><p> The OIC convened to discuss the Quran burnings after Iraq earlier in July expelled the Swedish ambassador and followers of a populist cleric stormed the country&#39;s embassy in Baghdad. The OIC last week suspended the credentials of Sweden&#39;s special envoy to the organization.</p><p> Coinciding with the IOC meeting, two Iraqi immigrants in Sweden burned a Quran outside the parliament building. Seven Quran burnings were planned in Denmark on Monday, following five similar protests on Sunday outside foreign embassies.</p><p> The Quran burnings have stirred anger among Muslim communities in Scandinavia. The imam of the Stockholm Central Mosque, where a protester burned a Quran last week, said Muslims in Sweden faced growing harassment. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-826883?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Police stand guard as a man, not pictured, prepared to burn a copy of the Quran during a demonstration in Stockholm on Monday.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: oscar olsson/Shutterstock</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> “We understand the need for freedom of expression, but we want something to change in how we are treated,” the imam, Mahmoud Khalfi, said. “The burning [of the Quran] is part of a bigger pattern of hatred here that makes us feel very unsafe,” he said, adding that many young Muslims had come to believe that Sweden was hostile to Islam, which could fuel extremism.</p><p> Swedish Prime Minister Ulf Kristersson said on Sunday that he would look at the country&#39;s laws to “consider measures to strengthen our national security and the security of Swedes in Sweden and in the world.”</p><p> The Danish government said it would explore the possibility of intervening in situations where “other countries, cultures, and religions are being insulted, and where this could have significant negative consequences for Denmark.”</p><p> Compared with 2005, when Denmark was at the center of global controversy after a Danish newspaper <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB113961902769071403?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">published cartoons depicting the Prophet Muhammad</a> , Copenhagen has taken a more compromising stance this time.</p><p> In part, it reflects Western countries&#39; need for Sweden and Denmark to repair diplomatic ties with Muslim governments in an effort to build a strong, global front against Russia, as US influence in the Middle East has waned, said Jakob Skovgaard-Petersen, professor of Islamic and Arabic studies at the University of Copenhagen.</p><p> “The geopolitical situation is different, not only because Russia is fishing in troubled waters,” he said, but also because US ties with Saudi Arabia have become strained under President Biden and Crown Prince Mohammed bin Salman.</p><p> Still, the potential moves to legislate against Quran burnings have triggered criticism in Scandinavia.</p><p> “It&#39;s a real paradigm shift,” said Jacob Mchangama, founder of the Future of Free Speech project, a collaboration between his think tank Justitia, Vanderbilt University in Nashville and Aarhus University, Denmark.</p><p> “Denmark and Sweden are, along with Norway, the most secular and progressive countries in the world,” he said. “It is a worrying signal to appease countries that implement the death penalty for blasphemy, rather than telling Danish Muslims who are full-fledged members of society that, as part of the social contract, you have to accept criticism of ideas.”</p><p> Skovgaard-Petersen said the protest by Muslim leaders against the Quran burnings was both a way to demonstrate their defense of Islam and an attempt to prevent public anger from erupting in their own streets by showing resolve. The expulsion of the Swedish ambassador from Baghdad, for example, escalated a diplomatic crisis with Stockholm, but also defused street protests, he said.</p><p class="articleTagLine"> — <em>Kate Vtorygina</em> contributed to this article.</p><p> Write to Sune Engel Rasmussen at <a href="mailto:sune.rasmussen@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">sune.rasmussen@wsj.com</a> and Humza Jilani at <a href="mailto:humza.jilani@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">humza.jilani@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Mon, 31 Jul 2023 19:48:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/muslim-nations-call-on-sweden-denmark-to-ban-quran-burnings-ae94907</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/muslim-nations-call-on-sweden-denmark-to-ban-quran-burnings-ae94907<author><![CDATA[Sune Engel RasmussenHumza Jilani]]></author><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>Censorship</category><category>社会/社区</category><category>国际关系</category><category>人权/公民自由</category><category>伊斯兰教</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>宗教</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>审查制度</category><category>社会</category><category>社区</category><category>国际关系</category><category>人权</category><category>公民权利</category><category>islam</category><category>政治</category><category>宗教</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Israel’s Arab Citizens Sit Out Protests Against Judicial Overhaul]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>许多人表示，争取犹太民主的斗争让他们感到疏远<figure><img src="https://images.wsj.net/im-826600/?width=1278&amp;size=1" alt="来自以色列雅法的律师阿贝德·卡布布 (Abed Kaboub) 表示，阿拉伯公民不觉得自己是以色列国家的一部分。" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>来自以色列雅法的律师阿贝德·卡布布表示，阿拉伯公民不觉得自己是以色列国家的一部分。科比·沃尔夫 (Kobi Wolf) 为《华尔街日报》<span>撰稿 科比·沃尔夫 (Kobi Wolf) 为《华尔街日报》撰稿</span></figcaption></figure><!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001097985"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001097985"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline">作者：多夫<span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/dov-lieber" itemprop="url" rel="author">·利伯 (Dov Lieber)</a></span>和<span class="author" itemprop="name">阿里·弗兰兹莱奇 (Ari Flanzraich)</span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 7 月 31 日中午 12:04 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/israels-arab-citizens-sit-out-protests-against-judicial-overhaul-c9402a4c"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bigtophero
"></div><p>特拉维夫——几个月来，数十万以色列人走上街头，反对总理本杰明·内塔尼亚胡限制该国最高法院权力的<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/israel-protests-judicial-overhaul-netanyahu-7e264a71?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">分裂计划</a>。一些人称这是一场为犹太国家灵魂而战的斗争，他们用几乎宇宙论的术语来形容这场战斗，因为他们为维护他们所说的反对未来独裁政府的唯一障碍而奋斗。</p><p>该国 200 万阿拉伯公民（占总人口的五分之一以上）基本上被排除在外。</p><p>乍一看，他们的缺席很奇怪。最高法院一直是阿拉伯公民权利最强有力的捍卫者之一。法律专家表示，政府限制法院权力并将更多控制权交给民选官员的计划可能会为旨在剥夺阿拉伯公民权利的立法铺平道路，从而对以色列少数民族造成最大伤害。</p><p>不过，以色列的阿拉伯人表示，他们长期以来一直感到与国家疏远，并且关于犹太人民未来的辩论与他们的日常问题（例如犯罪和失业）没有太大关系。许多人说他们已经感觉自己像二等公民。</p><p> “阿拉伯人不参与，因为他们不觉得自己是国家的一部分，而更像是一个附属物，”来自阿拉伯裔犹太人混居城市雅法的 41 岁律师阿贝德·卡布布 (Abed Kaboub) 说。</p><p>内塔尼亚胡政府表示，需要进行彻底改革<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/israel-netanyahu-government-judicial-overhaul-protests-862dffd3?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">，以重新调整司法系统</a>，该系统攫取了太多权力，且过于左倾。抗议者经常谈论所有人平等，包括该国的阿拉伯人口。但他们也严重利用犹太复国主义理想，将以色列描绘成犹太人的家园。抗议活动中到处都是以色列国旗，歌声中还唱着代表犹太灵魂的国歌“Hatikva”。</p><p>阿拉伯公民表示，这样的形象可能会让以色列的非犹太人感到反感。许多人认为，示威者的民主口号听起来很空洞，因为它们没有解决以色列对西岸的占领问题，那里有两百万巴勒斯坦人生活在以色列军事统治和<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/young-palestinians-battle-israeli-troops-and-the-palestinian-authority-deepening-unrest-11663761718?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">摇摇欲坠的巴勒斯坦权力机构的</a>混合之下。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-826649?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">阿拉伯与犹太混居城市雅法的一座清真寺。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：《华尔街日报》的科比·沃尔夫</p></figcaption></figure></div><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="841" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-826613?width=1260&amp;height=841" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">七月份，在特拉维夫举行的反对以色列政府司法改革计划的抗议活动中，以色列国旗随处可见。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：Kobi Wolf/彭博新闻</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>“把自己放在他们的位置上。聚集在以色列国旗周围并唱[国歌]不是他们会支持的事情，”居住在犹太阿拉伯城市海法的巴勒斯坦律师戴安娜·布图说。</p><p>特拉维夫和其他城市每周举行的示威活动已<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/israeli-protesters-pledge-to-intensify-civil-unrest-76b69af9?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">连续举行 30 周</a>，吸引了一小群挥舞巴勒斯坦旗帜的反占领抗议者。</p><p>全国抗议运动是全国各地示威团体的伞式组织，该组织表示，一些阿拉伯以色列人参加了海法的抗议活动，但也承认“合理的担忧可能阻止其他人加入”。</p><p>该组织表示：“通过认识到不同社区面临的独特挑战并重视不同的观点，我们努力建立信任和团结的桥梁。”</p><p>以色列一些阿拉伯公民长期奉行抵制政治进程的政策，这是对犹太国家理念反感的一部分。从历史上看，阿拉伯公民在全国选举中的投票率远低于犹太以色列人。</p><p>其他阿拉伯公民表示，抗议活动没有解决他们的具体问题，包括阿拉伯城镇的高贫困率和犯罪率。</p><p>对于许多阿拉伯以色列人来说，比如来自阿拉伯以色列城市乌姆法姆的 30 岁希伯来语教师艾哈迈德·马哈米德 (Ahmad Mahamid)，维护以色列自由民主的问题与他的社区面临的日常斗争无关。</p><p>根据以色列中央统计局的数据，与犹太以色列人相比，阿拉伯以色列人可能更贫穷，预期寿命更短，对生活的满意度也更低。他们长期以来一直抱怨政府资源分配方面的歧视导致他们的学校条件较差，缺乏住房和适当的基础设施。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="905" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-826630?width=1260&amp;height=905" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> 2021 年 3 月，在阿拉伯以色列城市乌姆法赫姆，阿拉伯抗议者站在一个竞选广告牌后面，广告牌上画着以色列总理本杰明·内塔尼亚胡。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：Ariel Schalit/美联社</p></figcaption></figure></div><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-826628?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">议员艾曼·奥德（中间穿着衬衫和西装外套）参加了反对内塔尼亚胡司法改革的抗议活动，并呼吁阿拉伯公民参与其中。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：Tsafrir Abayov/美联社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>阿拉伯城镇也遭受着<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/israel-palestinians-caught-in-escalating-cycle-of-violence-in-jerusalem-and-west-bank-11675001861?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">日益恶化的暴力事件</a>之苦。根据处理阿拉伯与犹太人关系的非营利组织亚伯拉罕倡议 (Abraham Initiatives) 的数据，今年有 111 名以色列阿拉伯公民在犯罪相关事件中丧生，比 2022 年同期增加了 135%。</p><p>马哈米德说：“他们忙于捍卫他们私人的小民主，而我们则忙于生存，避免任何可能随机击中我们的流弹。”</p><p>以色列最高法院过去曾废除旨在限制巴勒斯坦人和阿拉伯公民权利的法律。例如，法院在 2000 年具有里程碑意义的案件中表示，建立在国有土地上的犹太社区不能禁止阿拉伯人迁入。法院还废除了对任何呼吁抵制以色列的人实施制裁的立法，以及阻止巴勒斯坦人索赔损失的法律来自被占领西岸的以色列安全部队。</p><p>内塔尼亚胡的联盟由右翼、极端民族主义和宗教保守派政党组成，已讨论通过立法，通过禁止任何不承认以色列为犹太国家的政党进入议会（以色列议会），从而有效限制阿拉伯人的政治参与。今天的最高法院可能会否决此类立法，而司法改革可能会限制法院这样做的能力。</p><p>左翼阿拉伯犹太哈达什党领袖艾曼·奥德参加了一些抗议活动，并呼吁阿拉伯公民参与其中。</p><p> “阿拉伯社会必须加强对抗议活动的参与，”奥德本月早些时候在推特上写道。他写道：“尽管有合理的批评和挑战，但我们将成为第一个因进一步限制民主空间而受到伤害的人。” </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=B58B7540-4CF9-464C-A04F-C0E71926FD01&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fisraels-arab-citizens-sit-out-protests-against-judicial-overhaul-c9402a4c&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption">以色列医生周二举行罢工，当局在因总理本杰明·内塔尼亚胡政府进行的司法改革而发生骚乱的夜晚，强行将抗议者从道路上带走。照片：阿米尔·利维/盖蒂图片社<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div><p>尽管如此，为阿拉伯公民争取平等权利的团体表示，他们已经输掉了向法院提起的大部分案件。其中包括一项法律，在维护共同的共同价值观的基础上，有效地允许阿拉伯人口众多地区的小型犹太社区禁止阿拉伯人迁入。法院维持了另一项严格限制约旦河西岸阿拉伯以色列人和巴勒斯坦人婚姻的法律。最大的打击发生在 2018 年，当时法院在一项将以色列定义为犹太国家的法律上站在政府一边。</p><p>特拉维夫国家安全研究所的民意调查显示，阿拉伯以色列人对最高法院的信心近年来不断下降，从 2017 年的 75% 降至 2022 年的 42%。</p><p>但许多阿拉伯裔以色列人对这一波反政府抗议活动最大的抱怨是，示威者对约旦河西岸缺乏关注。自以色列 1967 年从约旦手中夺取领土以来，那里的巴勒斯坦人一直生活在以色列的军事占领之下。</p><p> “无论他们试图做什么，都不会改变以色列占领的事实，他们只是忽视这一事实，”来自阿拉伯以色列城镇塔伊贝的 29 岁教师哈桑·哈吉-叶海亚 (Hasan Haj-Yahya) 说。 “为什么我们要浪费日日夜夜去争取最终会巩固我们明知是虚假的国家形象的东西呢？” </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-826640?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">一名巴勒斯坦妇女走在被占领的约旦河西岸杰宁难民营受损的道路上。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：Majdi Mohammed/美联社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>写信给 Dov Lieber，邮箱为<a href="mailto:dov.lieber@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">dov.lieber@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Mon, 31 Jul 2023 16:04:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/israels-arab-citizens-sit-out-protests-against-judicial-overhaul-c9402a4c</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/israels-arab-citizens-sit-out-protests-against-judicial-overhaul-c9402a4c<author><![CDATA[Dov Lieber]]></author><category>华尔街日报</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>本杰明·内塔尼亚胡</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>政治</category><category>国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Catering to Your Midlife Crisis Is a Growing Business]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>新兴行业帮助那些寻求充实的第二幕的成年人<!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001086694"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="467" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-824308?width=700&amp;height=467" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">寿命的延长导致更多的人在 40 多岁、50 多岁和 60 多岁时寻找有意义的追求。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：iStock </p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001086694"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/anne-tergesen" itemprop="url" rel="author">安妮·特格森</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 7 月 31 日上午 10:00 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/midlife-crisis-money-business-companies-29dc2273"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p>美国人希望他们的<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-virtuous-midlife-crisis-11578830400?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">中年危机</a>变得更有成效。这为越来越多的公司、教练和顾问提供了数百万美元的机会。</p><p>有些程序是在线的，收费几百美元。其他活动则在异国情调的地点进行，提供豪华住宿、瑜伽和冲浪课程，费用为数千美元。有时会有折扣。</p><p> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/death-finances-and-how-many-of-us-get-our-money-needs-wrong-51a660a2?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">更长的寿命</a>为企业提供了动力，引导更多的人在 40 多岁、50 多岁和 60 多岁时寻找有意义的追求。一些心理学家将这一时期称为第二次成年期，在此期间，从行政人员到全职父母再到照顾者等身份塑造角色可能会消失，导致一些人重新评估。</p><p>现代老年学院（MEA）联合创始人奇普·康利（Chip Conley）表示：“在这个寿命越来越长、变化越来越大的时代，过渡是我们需要掌握的一项技能。”该学院提供在线和面对面的研讨会。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="467" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-824307?width=700&amp;height=467" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">现代老年学院联合创始人奇普·康利 (Chip Conley) 身穿白衬衫，他表示，年龄歧视会让中年人认为自己无关紧要。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：现代长者学院</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>一些研究表明，生活满意度在 40 多岁左右达到低点，这可能是因为<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/work-life-balance-is-their-second-priority-work-is-their-first-b069aeee?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">工作和家庭需求</a>带来的压力。这种权衡，加上<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/would-life-be-better-if-you-worked-less-3f49e69a?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">很少的时间进行自我反思</a>，让许多人不确定如何迎接他们的下一个篇章。</p><p>康利说，中年课程的讲师探讨的主题包括中年心理发展和<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/anti-ageism-workplace-language-biggest-school-district-368db30f?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">年龄歧视</a>，这可能会让人们相信自己“无关紧要，已经过时了，最好的时光已经过去了”。</p><p>他在<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/ABNB" class="">Airbnb</a>工作后创建了 MEA <span class="company-name-type">，</span>这家家庭共享公司的年轻创始人称他为现代长者，52 岁。研讨会旨在帮助参与者学习更好地应对压力过渡， <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/layoffs-tech-job-cuts-fired-survival-guide-how-to-get-hired-laid-off-employees-11667943893?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">包括裁员</a>、离婚和亲人去世。</p><h3>自我反思的空间</h3><p>与一些大学<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/for-60-000-these-colleges-help-older-workers-plot-encore-careers-a0060b9a?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">为接近职业生涯结束的成年人</a>推出的为期数月的学术课程一样，大多数中年课程都以 8 到 50 人为一组。</p><p> “这些项目为人们提供了空间和结构，不仅可以考虑他们在这个阶段想做什么，还可以考虑成为谁，”芭芭拉·瓦克斯曼说，</p>一位在 MEA 任教的老年学家。<p></p><p> 46 岁的纳迪亚·阿尔·亚法伊 (Nadia Al Yafai) 表示，她最近从一家英国保险公司的高级职位被解雇后，发现了 Midlife ReThink，这是一个价值 385 美元的在线计划。</p><p>她说，“中年反思”被证明具有变革性，并补充说，遇到其他同样感到无依无靠的人让她感到安慰。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="467" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-824305?width=700&amp;height=467" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Midlife ReThink 为寻求新方向的人们提供在线课程，其中一张幻灯片概述了人生的各个阶段。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：中年反思</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>该计划由专门研究劳动力性别和代际平衡的教练兼顾问 Avivah Wittenberg-Cox 于 2020 年发起，包括三个 90 分钟的在线课程，约有 25 名参与者。</p><p> “很多人都在经历自己的转变，就好像他们正在经历一些可怕的事情一样，”维滕伯格-考克斯说。她说，“社区是帮助人们认识到在这个年龄和阶段变得焦躁不安是正常的、可以预见的”并渴望改变的关键。</p><p> Al Yafai 表示，一项要求她定义未来七年想要什么的练习促使她开始了咨询业务。</p><p> “我从因不再是旧世界的一部分而感到有点失落，到意识到有一个新世界，人们在做真正有趣的事情，”她说。</p><h3> “我们仍然有价值”</h3><p> Reboot Partners 提供职业和其他转型方面的研讨会和辅导，今年在新墨西哥州圣达菲和纽约州萨格港组织了两次为期周末的静修活动，费用为 1,895 美元。联合创始人杰耶·史密斯 (Jaye Smith) 表示，参与者想象自己的完美生活，并讨论对变革的恐惧和动机。 </p><p></p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="700" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-824304?width=700&amp;height=700" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">现代老年学院在墨西哥校园举办的虚拟和现场研讨会旨在帮助参与者更好地应对压力过渡。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：现代长者学院</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>MEA 在墨西哥南下加利福尼亚州的一个海滨校园里教授有关重新创造职业、拥抱中年和优化寿命的课程。它还提供为期数周的关于过渡、目的和重新构建退休的在线课程，价格为 395 至 1,250 美元。它计划明年在新墨西哥州圣达菲开设一个校区。</p><p>丽莎·菲茨帕特里克 (Lisa Fitzpatrick) 表示，她于 2019 年首次参加 MEA，帮助她克服了成功的障碍。</p><p> 55 岁的 Fitzpatrick 博士创办了 Grapevine Health，为低收入社区发布在线健康信息。她很高兴有机会与资深企业家康利互动。</p><p>这位华盛顿特区的居民表示，一项识别自我限制信念的练习帮助她克服了对年龄太大而无法创业的恐惧。她五次返回巴哈参加创业和医疗保健研讨会。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          wrap
"><figure class="media-object-image img-wrap"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="639" height="959" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-824306?width=639&amp;height=959" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">丽莎·菲茨帕特里克说，参加现代老年学院帮助她克服了成功的障碍。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：罗恩·凯瑟</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>第一次访问时，她获得了为期 7 天的奖学金，目前费用为 4,000 至 5,500 美元。</p><p>菲茨帕特里克特别喜欢的一项运动是在海滩上堆放石头。 “这听起来有点呜呜，”她说。但在小石头上平衡一块大石头的任务帮助她克服了实现目标的心理障碍。 “MEA 帮助中年人认识到我们仍然有价值，”她说。</p><h3>寻找目标</h3><p>有些节目探索接下来的行为或灵性。</p><p>总部位于达拉斯的 Halftime Institute 提供的服务包括为期两天、价值 2,500 美元的情侣静修项目和价值 25,000 美元的全年项目。后者包括面对面和在线课程，以及关于人际关系、健康、信仰和找到自己使命的一对一辅导。</p><p> “并非所有经历过这种情况的人都是基督徒，但这就是我们的观点，”联席首席执行官吉姆·斯托尔伯格说。 “我们谈论的是使命，而不是目的。”</p><p>纽约联合神学院 (Union Theological Seminary) 提供为期 4 个月的 Encore Transition 计划，费用为 2,500 美元，其中包括中年灵性和寻找具有社会目的的工作等主题的虚拟会议。</p><p>顾问卡罗琳·巴克·卢斯 (Carolyn Buck Luce) 带领一群女性参加为期一周的在线项目，名为“十年游戏”，费用为 2,250 美元。它要求参与者设定目标来指导他们下一个十年的教育和目的等领域。</p><p> “这是为了能够声明你被召唤的目的，”卢斯说。</p><div class="media-object scope-web
          inline
